06:26.100 --> 06:33.960
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Janet Morris' four-volume Solistra series
has had a highly successful sales record. With this series, it's interesting to

06:33.960 --> 06:41.440
know that although the books themselves are explicitly science fiction, they're
packaged as fantasy. Right. The covers in all four of the novels feature a

06:41.440 --> 06:49.100
scantily clad, voluptuous woman holding a sword, a scene typical of countless
fantasy novels. And the spines of two of the novels actually say fantasy under

06:49.100 --> 06:57.780
the publisher's colophon. We asked Morris why the novels appeared with these
covers. The difference in that particular case was that Frederick Poles, who was

06:57.780 --> 07:07.260
my first editor and who knew what was science fiction, left. And the other, I
guess, operative difference was that at the point in time when they came out,

07:07.320 --> 07:15.400
they could get a bigger print run if they called it fantasy. So it was an
editorial difference rather than a real difference. But those covers did not

07:15.400 --> 07:20.740
help me, in the least, get those books to the kind of people that I thought
should be reading them.

07:28.720 --> 07:37.480
Here Morris goes on to tell us her feelings about science fiction and fantasy. I
didn't realize, because I was never a fan in the sense of someone who was hooked

07:37.480 --> 07:46.160
into the community, that there was this great dichotomy and hostility between
the science fiction people and the fantasy people, and that hardly anyone read

07:46.160 --> 08:00.040
both. There was very, almost no converse between the two. And having an open
mind as part of science and dealing with unsolved problems and questions is just

08:00.040 --> 08:09.240
as important as showing that you indeed do understand this or that particular
principle, which seems right now to be valid until next week. It turns out that,

08:09.400 --> 08:21.160
well, it just was fudge factor. So I don't know if there's a difference for me,
unfortunately. Fantasy right now seems to be where the writers go that don't do

08:21.160 --> 08:32.100
any homework and don't really understand either this world or the principles on
which fantasy was originally based, the Homeric tradition and a good sense of

08:32.100 --> 08:43.700
history and honor and all those nice things that we don't talk about too much
anymore. And science fiction is where people write who at least have a

08:43.700 --> 08:53.880
willingness to pay some lip service to a logical mind. Fantasy used to be a lot
better when most people were writing it. But right now, there's a lot of very

08:53.880 --> 09:03.840
mediocre writers writing, you know, good and evil fantasy or warmed-over
Christian mythology, which is not, to me, what fantasy is about. I love Conan,

09:04.040 --> 09:14.220
you know, original Howard stuff and all the real old stuff and Homer and Hesiod.
That, to me, is good fantasy. Science fiction, when it's good, is great.

09:18.320 --> 09:28.820
The problem exists in science fiction in a different form where the young
writers who don't really have a good conceptual basis in science fiction use

09:28.820 --> 09:39.240
what I call nuts and bolts, which is just data that they can get from
encyclopedias as their science and have a little trick ending in which some

09:39.240 --> 09:50.960
scientific principle is invoked to resolve the plot. But for me, good science
fiction has the science as an integral part of the development of the story. And

09:50.960 --> 10:03.400
you couldn't have the story without the scientific principle or the theoretical
questions that you're basing it on. In other words, if you can take the science

10:03.400 --> 10:11.860
out of it and you've still got a story, then you shouldn't have science fiction.
It should be something else. TV. Something like that. But science fiction should

10:11.860 --> 10:21.120
have almost the science or the theory or the world or whatever you want to call
it, the structure that you're making. It adds the central character. And that's

10:21.120 --> 10:28.740
what it does. When it does it best, it frees the mind and allows people to come
away with lots of good questions that they can think about rather than providing

10:28.740 --> 10:35.180
tad answers, which indeed have a very limited lifespan, as we've all seen. More
with Janet Morris on our next show.

