12:08.500 --> 12:17.200
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Science Fiction author Janet Morris' Saga
of the Carrion Empire is a trilogy comprising Dream Dancer, Cruiser Dreams, and

12:17.200 --> 12:25.220
Earth Dreams. The time is the 23rd century. In the milieu is Earth and several
human-colonized planets and faraway star systems. The heroine is Shebot, a

12:25.220 --> 12:33.120
teenager from Earth, which by this time has reverted to a medieval culture. The
trilogy describes her coming of age as a ward of the rulers of the human empire,

12:33.320 --> 12:41.260
the Carrion family. The saga of the Carrion Empire is an exciting blend of
characterization, speculative physics, and political intrigue. We asked Morris

12:41.260 --> 12:49.400
if she plotted the whole series in detail before she wrote it. I was going to do
three. I signed for them before I did them. Three was all there was going to be.

12:49.620 --> 12:56.700
Three is all there is going to be. You know, unless something drastically
changes, then I see where it's someplace that I'd like to take it. I knew

12:56.700 --> 13:06.640
exactly what I wanted to talk about the physics and the rest of it. I wanted to
create a female character that had all the flaws that Estre did not, that was

13:06.640 --> 13:18.460
totally opposite. And to talk a little about politics, I come from a very
political background. My half-sister was Carter, a speechwriter on economic

13:18.460 --> 13:29.980
policy. I know way too much about politics to suit me. And I wanted to talk a
little bit about politics and decision-making at higher levels and what indeed

13:29.980 --> 13:45.460
happens to the people involved in it and the people affected by it who have no
control of it. And the nice stuff for me that balanced it off was a culture that

13:45.460 --> 13:53.780
was comfortable with its technology growing into its technology, growing along
with its technology. And, I mean, for me, the cruisers were the main characters

13:53.780 --> 14:06.020
there. I loved doing the cruiser sections, although they were very difficult at
times, to make it really seem as if they were cruisers. And, you know, one never

14:06.020 --> 14:16.180
knows if one succeeds, but for me, they really were cruisers. Plus, I had the
whole of history to draw on. Instead of having a culture that had nothing to do

14:16.180 --> 14:23.640
with us, I had a culture that had everything to do with us. There had been no
collapse, no World War III. Everything had proceeded apace and just gotten

14:23.640 --> 14:31.400
worse. The problems with quantum mechanics hadn't been solved. The problems with
nothing else had been solved, and we were just sort of muddling along the way we

14:31.400 --> 14:41.480
tend to do. And that, to me, was a lot of fun. But, as I said, I did the
partial, and it went to auction in two countries on the partial. And I was sold

14:41.480 --> 14:50.760
it here in England at the same time. Had two editors. Trying to keep the volumes
consistent. You know, every editor has a different idea of what exactly they

14:50.760 --> 14:59.660
want you to do, and they all want to mix in. It's very seldom you get an editor
that leaves you totally alone. It doesn't bother you at all about a book. And I

14:59.660 --> 15:07.520
had to split the difference on one occasion between them, where one editor
wanted one section to be longer, and the other one wanted the same section to be

15:07.520 --> 15:16.140
shorter, in the same, just the same 30 pages. And I think I ended up doing a
prologue, which seemed to satisfy them both. I think they forgot what they asked

15:16.140 --> 15:25.660
me to do, but I had to do something super. So I had done that. So they were cold
-bloodedly meant to be exactly what they are. Morris told us that she wrote this

15:25.660 --> 15:34.380
trilogy with the mature, literate, scientifically sophisticated reader in mind.
Apparently, her strategy worked. So I'd go to these conventions, and they'd all

15:34.380 --> 15:41.460
raise their hands and say, yes, they want more science, and yes, they were ready
to work a little, and yes, they wanted to be challenged. And I said, okay, but

15:41.460 --> 15:53.480
we don't. And I wrote a book in which I wrote to my ideal reader, didn't talk
down, didn't simplify it, did what I consider a good job of explaining

15:53.480 --> 16:02.160
mathematics as poetry, and just let fly. And so far, the reaction to it's been
very good. As I told you, the first printing, it's been through two printings

16:02.160 --> 16:11.360
before publication, Earth Dreams, and it's been doing very well. You get some
people that don't want to work, but I think there's enough story there to carry

16:11.360 --> 16:17.280
them over the parts that they are not willing to try to understand. More with
Janet Morris on our next show.

