17:55.740 --> 18:02.600
of high quality, and when one reads them, it's apparent she's done her homework
on all facets of the novels. The characters, the science, the background,

18:02.940 --> 18:10.480
everything. We wondered if Morris uses feedback from her fans. We asked her
initially if she goes to science fiction conventions. Her answer reveals a lot

18:10.480 --> 18:19.840
about how a writer approaches her work. I used to go to more conventions than I
do now. One, because I've been doing books out of genre. I don't go a lot. And

18:19.840 --> 18:30.280
my research, when I'm researching, takes up a tremendous amount of time. Two,
because I'm just, on one hand, I'm arrogant and I like to control things. On the

18:30.280 --> 18:38.120
other hand, I'm very sensitive and I can always manage to get offended at
something somebody says. I was guest of honor at Carracon last year. I did that

18:38.120 --> 18:49.260
one. And I'm going to do Lunacon in March because I really like that New York
crowd. Otherwise, I mean, my writing schedule is very heavy. I've got, I just

18:49.260 --> 19:02.580
turned in a book. I just started a book, which is doing just about the amount of
time I have to finish it. I don't have a lot of extra time to do more than the

19:02.580 --> 19:10.440
work that I'm doing. I'm real conscientious on my homework. And a lot of times
there's, you can never know enough about the subjects that you're writing about.

19:10.540 --> 19:16.700
And when you're creating a whole world, you find there's something that you need
to know that you haven't. I mean, physics alone will not get you through a

19:16.700 --> 19:24.540
science fiction novel, nor will any other specialty, not biology. There's no
single thing you can do that's going to allow you to create an entire culture

19:24.540 --> 19:35.340
and change it. It's not just creating the culture. You've got to be able to
create it and change it. So the homework really takes a tremendous amount of

19:35.340 --> 19:47.020
effort. And it's nice to do a fantasy book now almost as a break or a pay
vacation because that homework I did years ago. And I remember all the things I

19:47.020 --> 19:56.020
need to know to do that. I think I have like three books on my desk. Heraclitus
Cacchus, Fragments, one on Asian fighting styles, and a classical dictionary

19:56.020 --> 20:04.720
from Oxford. And that is all I need rather than, you know, three shelves and the
stool and a pile on the floor of stuff that I have to be able to refer to all

20:04.720 --> 20:05.120
the time.

20:16.280 --> 20:29.780
So cons, the kind of feedback you get at cons isn't as good as I get feedback
through letters, but sales figures and letters are really the way. And also, you

20:29.780 --> 20:38.380
know, there are readers around here. I do some, you know, I do book signings and
I do small things where I can control it a little better than I can at the real

20:38.380 --> 20:49.260
big, I mean, I'll do a world con or I went to England for C-Con. I do one or two
a year, but it's really all the time that I want to give it. It takes me about a

20:49.260 --> 20:59.020
week. It's a different person that has to go to a con. My writer is too open. So
I had to create this other person, my author, and the author goes to the cons.

20:59.020 --> 21:06.480
And it takes me about a week to get rid of this author afterwards because when
you sit at that typewriter, there's no room for you, the writer. You have to

21:06.480 --> 21:17.840
erase yourself so that the characters can be there and the story can come. And
if I'm self-conscious or somebody has said something to me about there being too

21:17.840 --> 21:27.240
much science or not enough science or that my books are fantasators to get
really upset with those fantasy labels, I'm liable to take it too much to heart

21:27.240 --> 21:36.040
and to react to it on paper and do something to my story, which I don't want to
happen because it's something that's happened. I just got a real good review in

21:36.040 --> 21:45.280
the New York Daily News and I hate the good ones as much as I hate the bad ones.
They never like them for the right reasons. So the best thing really is just the

21:45.280 --> 21:53.840
letters from people, you know, who read them three times and loved them or who
ask me intelligent questions, which I try to answer. More with Janet Morris on

